	<item>
		<title>About us</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/about/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 20 Feb 2012 23:40:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=6</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />

The short version is this:
I love God, my family and life. I thrive on seeing changed lives through group environments. I worked as a Student Pastor and College Pastor for 8 years at Chestnut Mountain Church in Flowery Branch, Georgia.  Over the years, I have been the key speaker at camps, retreats and Disciple Now weekends all over the southeastern US. On occasion, I have had the honor of teaching during corporate worship gatherings on Sunday mornings.

Not only am I passionate about my faith I am also very passionate about business.
I co-founded a corporate development and team building company called lapdog inc. and enjoyed great success for more than 9 years and facilitated meetings for thousands of corporate groups. I have enjoyed traveling all over the world helping teams become more effective.   I have had the privilege of working with many of the top fortune 100 companies in the world.
Here are a few of the companies I have worked with:

Air France
American Express
AT&amp;T
Auto Trader
Babies “R” Us
Bank of America
Bell South
Cargill
Citigroup
CNN
Coca-Cola Enterprises
Coke Company
Credigy
Epson America, Inc.
Frito Lay
Georgia Tech
Intercontinental Hotels Group
NASCAR
Office Depot
Pulte Homes
Scientific Atlanta
Siemens
Sprint/Nextel
Starbucks
University of Georgia
UPS
USG Corporation
Wayne Farms
ZS Associate

I would love the chance to work with you and your organization.  To see how you can be a part of this exciting movement <a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/member-benifits-join-now/">click here</a>.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Who do we serve?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/whodoweserve/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 10 Jun 2012 21:52:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=76</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[At the discussion project simplicity is the name of the game.  We have tried to make the process and education process as fun and simple as we can without sacrificing content.  Here is how the process works for us.  The process we have  is pretty simple.   Each online session will last two months.  We have six sessions planned that build on the skills and techniques you have learned from the previous sessions.

<strong>Step one:</strong>

Stroll around our site and get a feel for who we are and what we stand for.  If you have done that and now your ready for the next step then lets get started.

&nbsp;

<strong>Step two:</strong>

Decide s the level of membership that best fits you where you are in your journey with your group. You will then be prompted to to fill out an online inquiry form so we can find out a little more about you.  Once we have received your inquiry and processed it, you will be getting a call from a discussion project representative<em>.(We are not accepting memberships until September 1st.  You can send us an email at Greg@thediscussionproject to be one of the first to sign up for special rates.)</em>

&nbsp;

<strong>Step 3:</strong>

Once we have finished the enrollment process.  You will receive a welcome packet in your email layout everything you need to do for the membership you signed up for. If you are doing online sessions there will be a download you will have to do before the first session.  The online session software we will be using is ooVoo.  There will instruction in the welcome packet for all downloads and preparations that need to happen.

&nbsp;

<strong>Step 4:</strong>

Let the festival of learning and online community began.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Statement of faith</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/about/statement-of-faith/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Jun 2012 16:53:38 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=112</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[The discussion project is not affiliated to any denomination or any church. The purpose of this organization is to equip people with skills and abilities to lead groups in their personal and professional lives.  Our Faith is important to us, so therefore I want you to know where we stand on the issue of faith.

<strong>God:</strong>  We believe there is only one true God that exist in three persons. God the Father, God the Son,God the Holy Spirit. We believe is the creator of all things. We also believe he is loving, righteous, and  all knowing.

<strong>People:</strong>We believe we were all created by God in His image.  We were made to God’s glory.  We are all born into this world broken.  God desires to to have a relationship with us even in our broken state.

<strong>The scriptures:</strong>  Is the way that God reveals himself to us and shows us the truth of who we are and who He is. It is accurate, reliable and the foundation of our faith.

<strong>Salvation:</strong> Salvation comes from Christ and Christ alone.  We believe this is the act of placing your faith in Christ and allowing his grace and forgiveness to cover your sin with the price he paid on the cross.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Core values/ idea statement</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/about/core-values-idea-statement/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Jun 2012 17:03:07 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=115</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p id="internal-source-marker_0.5187089448090195" dir="ltr">This is the heartbeat of The Discussion Project</p>
<strong>Relationships:</strong>
We believe investing in genuine relationships will change people and the world around us.
What are you doing to build your Personal and Professional relationships?

<strong>Discovery</strong>:
If you don't seek you won’t find and if you don’t listen you won’t hear.
What are you looking for?

<strong>Generosity</strong>:
We pray that God reminds us that this stuff is not ours
What am I willing to give away?

<strong>Creativity</strong>:
Creating is a God thing.
Have you created something in the last six months? If no, why not?

<strong>Fun:</strong>
Laugh til you cry.  Its will make you a better person to be around.
When is the last time you laughed until you hurt?

<strong>Vision/Idea statement :</strong>
We want to create meaningful conversations, that will lead to life change.   We will attempt this by helping leaders develop the art of facilitation.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Disciple Now/ Retreat  Discussion leaders</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/membership/disciple-now-retreat-discussion-leaders/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Jun 2012 19:34:01 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=129</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<strong>Online  DNOW/Retreat group leader training   ($16 per person for each session)</strong>
<ul>
	<li>each session is limited to only 12 participants</li>
	<li>these sessions will be be 60 to 100 minutes.</li>
	<li>These sessions will be done live online using our conference software.</li>
	<li>There will be printable handouts that will be emailed to you once the sessions are finished.</li>
	<li>There material is designed specifically for group leaders that will be leading groups for a short time, such as a weekend or week long camp.</li>
	<li>We  will cover basic topics such as: group dynamics, How groups process information,  How different age groups process information differently, tips on keeping dicussion going, and basic tips on asking great questions.</li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Organizations  / Church leaders</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/membership/organizations-church-leaders/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 27 Jun 2012 19:34:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?page_id=131</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Online Organizational leader facilitator training

($119 for each 2 month session)
<ul>
	<li>each session is limited to only 12 participants.  These 12 participants will remain in the same discussion sessions together for the 2 months.</li>
	<li>each session will last 2 months</li>
	<li>You will have the chance to participate in 4 online discussions with 11 other participants.</li>
	<li>each online session will last 40 to 50 minutes.</li>
	<li>A private message board for you and the 11 others in the session.  This way you can discuss things that came up in the online session or just bounce ideas off each other.</li>
	<li>A personal one on one coaching session with a TDP facilitator to help work on application of the topic covered that month.  The call will last 40 to 50 minutes.</li>
	<li>these sessions are video sessions, so we can interact with each other during the call.</li>
	<li>If you sign up for more than two sessions you will receive a free lifetime membership to the Whiteboard Center.  If you participate in all 6 sessions you will receive 2 free ebooks.</li>
	<li>There will also be weekly emails re-enforcing the topics we are covering for that session.</li>
	<li>some session have online assessments that will also be taken online</li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>And.....</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/i-love-groups/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 21 Feb 2012 03:45:17 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>jointhetalk</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=16</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/coke-zero4.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-40" title="coke-zero" src="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/02/coke-zero4-285x300.jpg" alt="" width="285" height="300" /></a>

How many times have you been a conversations with someone and they makes a statement, and you respond with "yeah but"?  Instead of "yeah but"  what if you said "and". The conversation would then take on an entirely new attitude. . The conversation will become more positive just because you are focusing on what could be.    Next time you are in a group discussion give it a try.   Go an entire conversation and don"t say "but".  Replace it with "and".  You may not have the same response that the guy in the commercial did but, it will turn the conversation into a more productive positive experience.

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iuIu8R1W3Ys

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>What is your smile saying?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/what-is-your-smile-saying/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 15 Jul 2012 14:55:10 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=23</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/3df00b1b5d5b1bc52e8817fed5b732ce1.jpeg"><img class=" wp-image-48 alignnone" title="3df00b1b5d5b1bc52e8817fed5b732ce" src="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/3df00b1b5d5b1bc52e8817fed5b732ce1-300x224.jpg" alt="" width="270" height="202" /></a><a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/78671515ea703f80e46c5aec80d0a16a2.jpeg"><img class="wp-image-49 alignnone" title="78671515ea703f80e46c5aec80d0a16a" src="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/78671515ea703f80e46c5aec80d0a16a2-300x181.jpg" alt="" width="336" height="202" /></a>

Science has proven that the more you smile, the more positive reactions others will give you.  There are lots of  types of smiles but, today I would love to discuss the Tight-lipped smile.

The tight-lipped smile shows I have a secret and I'm not going to be sharing it with you anytime soon.  This smile is seen in magazine pictures of successful businessmen who are communicating, "I have the secrets of success and you've got to try and guess what they are."   In most of these interviews, the men talk a lot about principles of success, but rarely do the reveal the exact details of how they succeeded. (Herman Cain Pictured above left) On the other hand there is Richard Branson (picture aboveright) who is always seen sporting a wide toothy smile and is happy to explain the exact details of his success because he knows that most people wont do it anyway.  So what is your smile telling others about you today?  Try smiling when you greet someone, the interaction will more times than none be more positive.

So the big question is, What is your facing saying about you today?

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Right or Left?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/right-or-left/</link>
		<pubDate>Sun, 22 Jul 2012 10:00:36 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=57</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Mercedes-Benz-Left-Brain-Right-Brain2-667x472.jpg"><img class="alignleft  wp-image-58" title="Mercedes-Benz-Left-Brain-Right-Brain2-667x472" src="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/Mercedes-Benz-Left-Brain-Right-Brain2-667x472-300x211.jpg" alt="" width="352" height="247" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

It is very important to know your participants and how they think and work.  The more I know about each person the more time I can spend in developing a method or process that will each person process the information I am trying to share.   Have you ever wonder if you are a right brain thinker or a left brain thinker.

<strong>People who are left brain are usually good at or like to do:</strong>

* Prefer Classical Music
* Your Left-Brain controls the right side of your body
* Prefer things like instructions to be done verbally
* Good at math
* Like to read
* Follow Western Thought*
* Very Logical
* Dog lovers
* Don't enjoy clowning around
* Can't be hypnotized
* Usually remember things only specifically studied
* Need total quiet to read or study
* Like to read realistic stories
* Like to write non-fiction
* Prefer individual counseling
* Enjoy copying or tracing pictures and filling in details
* Also like to read action stories
* Usually rational
* Usually do things in a planned orderly way
* If you have to answer someone's question, you won't let your peronal feelings get in the way
* Good at algebra
* Can remember verbal material
* Almost never absent minded
* Like to tell stories but not act them out
* Can think better sitting down
* Like to be a music critic
* Attentive during long verbal explanations
* Prefer well structured assignments over open ended ones
* Read for specific details and facts
* Skilled at sequencing ideas
* Likes to be Organized

&nbsp;

<strong>People who are right brain are usually good at or like to do:</strong>

* Prefer rock music
* Right brain controls left side of body
* Prefer visual instructions with examples
* Good at sports
* Good at art
* Follow Eastern thought*
* Cat lovers
* Enjoy clowning around
* Can be hypnotized
* Like to read fantasy and mystery stories
* Can listen to music or TV while studying
* Like to write fiction
* Prefer group
* Fun to dream about things that will probably never happen
* Enjoy making up own drawings and images
* Good at geometry
* Like organizing things to show relation
* Can memorize music
* Occasionally absentminded
* Like to act out stories
* Enjoy interacting affectively with others
* Think better when lying down
* Become restless during long verbal explanations
* Enjoy creative storytelling
* Prefer to learn through free exploration
* Good at recalling spatial imagery
* Read for main details
* Skilled in showing relationships between ideas
* Preference for summarizing over outlining
* Solve problems intuitively
* Very Spontaneous and unpredictable
* Dreamer
* philosophical

Here is a link to a short test to see if you are a right brain or left brain thinker.

<a href="http://www.intelliscript.net/test_area/questionnaire/questionnaire.cgi">Are you a "right" or "left" brain thinker?</a>

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[Online individual group leader training   ($34 for each 2 month session)
<ul>
	<li>each session is limited to only 12 participants</li>
	<li>You can participate in one on-line discussion each month if you chose.</li>
	<li>each session will last 2 months</li>
	<li>There will also be  bi weekly emails re-enforcing the topics we are covering for that session.</li>
	<li>each online session will last 40 to 50 minutes.</li>
	<li>If you sign up for more than four sessions you will receive a free lifetime membership to the Whiteboard Center.</li>
	<li>There will be downloadable podcast only to the members of these sessions</li>
	<li>There material is designed specifically for groups</li>
</ul>]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>What? So what. Now what?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=153</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 1970 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=153</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />
Do you remember the first time you used an apple product?  <strong>What</strong> was it like?

<strong>So what</strong> changed for you after that experience?  If nothing changed <strong>why not</strong>?

<strong>Now</strong> do you presently use any apple products? <strong> Why</strong>?

Here are 4 questions that can get your group to talking.
What?  So what?  Now What? and Why?
The biggest thing to remember is ask questions don't make statements.It takes some practice but these four simple questions can give you lots of great feedback.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>What?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/what/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 20 Jul 2012 12:43:46 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=189</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/61af5c5c21462eb4cafcad6bee043318.jpeg"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-190" title="61af5c5c21462eb4cafcad6bee043318" src="http://thediscussionproject.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/61af5c5c21462eb4cafcad6bee043318.jpeg" alt="" width="174" height="217" /></a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Do you remember the first time you used an apple product?  <strong>What</strong> was it like?

<strong>So what</strong> changed for you after that experience?  If nothing changed <strong>why not</strong>?

Now do you presently use any apple products?  <strong>Why</strong>?

Here are 4 questions that can get your group to talking.

What?  So what?  Now What? and Why?
Be creative with how you ask these questions but be care not to go to deep to quick.  If your your questions get to personal to quick most of your group members will check out.  Just be patient and don't push for participants to talk. The biggest thing to remember is, ask questions don't make statements.It takes some practice but these four simple questions can give you some great feedback and discussions.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>3 simple questions.</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/3-simple-questions/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 25 Jul 2012 10:59:43 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=202</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />

This exercise is used to get to the real issue.  This exercise is not for every situation, so you have to use your judgment.  This exercise is used for a one on one situation.  Here are the guidelines to fallow; You cannot give the same answer twice,  You ask these three questions in this order.  then repeat the process over and over until you feel like you have gotten to the root of the issue. It will sometimes take up to 4 to 5 times before they start to really share what is going on. This exercise is extremely interceptive, so give the person time to think about an answer but don't let them get distracted and get off point.  Let me know if you use this and how it goes.

What are you doing?

What do you want to do?

What are you going to do?]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Me?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/me/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 27 Jul 2012 10:30:52 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=206</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/png;base64," alt="" />

If there is one thing true in this world is that we like to talk about ourselves.  We would never come out and say that to someone because it seems wrong to say out loud.  I find myself doing it all the time.  Have you ever wondered why this is?  Test this and see.  Ask someone in your sphere a few questions such as:  So what's new with you?  Whats your plans for this weekend?  Ask a question about something going on in there life and see what happens. See if they ask you the same questions.  If you listen to what they are saying you can hear what they are really passionate about.  It may take a little time but just sit and listen and ask more questions.  Here is cool exercise if your interested,  take one conversation you will have today and do nothing but ask questions.  When you feel like you want to make a statement, don't ask a question.  You will learn something new about them I promise.  This exercise is just a simple way to help us realize life sometimes needs to be about someone other than ourselves.]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Trust</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/trust/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 30 Jul 2012 14:53:49 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=211</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />
<div><img id=":6y" src="https://mail.google.com/mail/images/cleardot.gif" alt="" data-tooltip="Show details" /></div>
<div id=":xb">
<div id=":xa">

Rarely will you here me say things like:  here are three steps to a better group... or five ways to turn your group around... but there are a few things that are essential to having a great group experience with great relationships.  The single biggest factor for a groups success is Trust.  The level of trust in your group will directly affect the growth and stability of your group.  Trust is one of those core values in relationships we don't talk a lot about until it has been broken or damaged.  The reality is without some form of trust there is really no relationship, and all great groups are built on strong relationships.  I have a few questions I would love to ask if you are willing to be honest with yourself:

What level of trust would you say you are at in your group? On a scale of 1-10,  (1) being I don't trust this person at all and (10) being I will share my deepest darkest secrets know else knows.

What would you not share in your group?

What would you not share in your group?

What have you shared from your group about your personal life? Did anyone else follow and share also?

Do you trust that what is shared in your group stays in your group?

I want to propose a simple idea to help us raise the level of trust in our groups and each other. What if we started all our conversations with Trust and not with distrust?  For example: Instead of saying "I can't believe you said that or did that to them." How about "Help me understand what happened to make you react that way?"  We could go on and on but the real question we each have to answer is why do we inter most conversations with distrust instead of trust.

</div>
</div>
&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

		<title>Is trust about control?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=216</link>
		<pubDate>Thu, 01 Jan 1970 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=216</guid>
		<description></description>

		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>216</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date>2012-08-01 10:59:06</wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt>0000-00-00 00:00:00</wp:post_date_gmt>

	<item>
		<title>Is trust about control?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/is-trust-about-control/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 01 Aug 2012 15:04:32 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=217</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">I work hard to try and make my blog post short and to the point.  I'm not much for word post that wait until the end to make the point, but this subject of trust is so difficult to simplify.  I want you to take a minute and think about that one person in your life that you trust with all the areas of your life.  What role or actions did you take to help that relationship reach that level of Trust?  A deep level of trust will always take time, energy and effort to build.  I believe control is one of the big issues at the foundation of a deep trusting relationship.  It's hard for us to give control of a part of our lives to someone else and trust they are going to do and be what they promised, but that is how strong lasting relationships are built.  If you want to build some deeper relationships with others then you need to take the first steps with trusting them and giving up some control.</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;"></div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">Here are a few questions for you to discuss in your group:</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;"></div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">Why is it so hard/easy for you to trust other people?</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;"></div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">How many people in your life would you say are close friends that you share a deep trusting relationship?</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;"></div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">Is it hard for you to give up control of some things in your life? Why?</div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;"></div>
&nbsp;
<div class="ennote" style="word-wrap: break-word;">What are you going to do this week to build trust with someone in your group?</div>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>217</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date>2012-08-01 11:04:32</wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt>2012-08-01 15:04:32</wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status>open</wp:comment_status>
		<wp:ping_status>open</wp:ping_status>
		<wp:post_name>is-trust-about-control</wp:post_name>
		<wp:status>publish</wp:status>
		<wp:post_parent>0</wp:post_parent>
		<wp:menu_order>0</wp:menu_order>

	<item>
		<title>Who am I?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/do-i-trust-myself/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 07 Aug 2012 13:40:31 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=222</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img id="il_fi" src="http://uptownmagazine.com/files/2012/03/UPTOWN_woman_looking_in_mirror-585x383.jpg" alt="" width="585" height="383" />

When you look in the mirror what do you see?

What do you think about the way you look and feel?

As crazy as it sounds the way we see ourselves comes out in the way we communicate and deal with other people.  If you want to know the single biggest thing that could help you in life and in your pursuit of becoming a great leader, it would be to work on your self image.  I'm not talking about the way you look but the way you see yourself and the way others see you.  If you want to lead others you must first look inside and lead yourself. Here are some questions to help you get started.

Do you like being around people more than being alone?

Do you like to read self help books or fiction books?

Would you rather watch a movie instead of reading a book?

Do you know the exact or close to exact amount of money in your bank account right now?

These are just a few questions to get you started in the right direction.  I would encourage you to be very honest with yourself about who you are, not who you wish you were.  You can change some things later, but let's first realize where you are before we chat about where you want to go.  If you are having problems with this exercise find a close friend and tell them what you are doing.  This exercise will be difficult at times but if its not then your not really being honest with yourself. If you find yourself asking more questions that is the point.  In session 101 we will look deeper into this concept.  So the million dollar question is, when you look in the mirror who do you see?

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>222</wp:post_id>

		<wp:comment_status>open</wp:comment_status>

		<wp:post_name>do-i-trust-myself</wp:post_name>

		<category domain="category" nicename="who-am-i"><![CDATA[Sesion 101 Who are you?]]></category>

	<item>
		<title>Does it really matter where we meet?</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/does-it-really-matter-where-we-meet/</link>
		<pubDate>Fri, 31 Aug 2012 11:02:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=230</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />

This is a question that all group leaders ask themselves at some point.  My answer would be yes and no.  The reason I say that is because you as the leader control the environment and can change it at anytime according to the mood you want to set.  The environment you create for your group is as important as the content you will be sharing.  As leaders of groups we spend the majority of our time on content and information but rarely do we spend time thinking about the setting in which we will share the content.  Here are a few things to think about before your next group meeting:

<strong>What is the mood of the room or place you will be meeting? </strong>

Does this group take place in the morning, mid day or evening?  How will the participants be dressed?  The time of day and attire of participants will set the tone of your gathering.
<div>

<strong>Is the room comfortable? </strong>

Are you looking to share information or to have personal conversations about an issue or topic?

</div>
<strong>What are the distractions where you are meeting?</strong>                                <wbr>      </wbr>

Can you minimize or do away with distractions completely?

The environment you help create could allow the content that is being shared to reach the participants in a new and creative way.  Before your next group gathering think about the environment that the group will be walking into. To learn more about environment check out the how to get involved with TDP. <a href="http://thediscussionproject.com/howdoesitwork/">HERE.</a>

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

		<title>Rows or Circles?</title>

I Heard a pastor make a statement the other day that caught my attention.  He said"Discipleship and true community don't happen in rows but happens in circles."  What do you think?]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Front loading</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/front-loading/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 29 Aug 2012 18:11:09 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=237</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>
<div>
<div>Ocean Front Cabana</div>
<div>7 / 7</div>
</div>
<div>
<div><img src="http://photos.luxurylink.us/images/sho_4fda04d0/2135_9107-auto-578/Ocean%2BFront%2BCabana.jpg" alt="" /></div>
</div>
</div>
Front loading may be a term that you don't use much but it is a part of our lives all the time.  Think of front loading like a preview of what is to come or building up excitement over an experience your group is about to have.

I just finished planning my honeymoon to Belize and I have to say I am so excited.  We will be spending 5 nights in a private cabana on a small island 7 miles off the coast of Belize.  There will be fresh coffee and tea delivered to our cabana each morning.  We have our own hammock on the front porch of our cabana.   We will have six days or relaxation, snorkeling, cave tubing and loads of fun.  You get the idea of what we will be experiencing on our honeymoon.  That is the idea of front loading.

As group leaders, we rarely take time to front load the group on what they are about to experience.  You can change the attitudes and perceptions of your participants using this method.  Think about the last time you went on vacation or went to the movies.  Did you talk about it before you went to build excitement?  Spend some time thinking of some creative ways you can get the group interested and talking about the topic you will be discussing before they ever arrive at the gathering.]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>Realities and Values</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/realaties-and-values/</link>
		<pubDate>Tue, 04 Sep 2012 14:01:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=251</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[In Steven Coveys book<a href="http://www.amazon.com/The-Habits-Highly-Effective-People/dp/0743269519"><em> 7 Habits of Highly effective people</em></a> , one of his keys points is for us to be careful how we "see" the world.  Not how we actually see the world with sight but how we perceive, interpret, and understand the world around us.

Covey explains that our point of view is divided into two main categories,  <em>The way things are</em> (realities<em>) and the way things should be</em> (values) We interpret our experiences from these two perspectives, rarely questioning their accuracy.

In short, we simply <em>assume</em> that the way we see things is the way they really are or the way they should be.  Our attitudes and behaviors are based on these assumptions.  Therefore, our point of view influences the way we think and the way we act.

Covey got the following experiment  from Harvard Business school and I would love to share it with you guys today.  The experiment is intended to demonstrate how two people can see the same thing, disagree—and yet <em>both</em> be right.

These are pictures from Coveys book.
<h2>Illustrations of a Young Woman</h2>
Look closely at the following illustrations, focusing first on the one on the left—and then slowly shift over to the one on the right:

<img src="http://www.ocdqblog.com/resource/WindowsLiveWriter-ThePointofViewParadox_9AE6-?fileId=7217885&amp;__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1275768956362" alt="" />

<strong>Can you see the young woman with the petite nose, wearing a necklace, and looking away from you in both illustrations? </strong>

&nbsp;
<h2>Illustrations of an Old Lady</h2>
Look closely at the following illustrations, focusing first on the one on the left—and then slowly shift over to the one on the right:

<img src="http://www.ocdqblog.com/resource/WindowsLiveWriter-ThePointofViewParadox_9AE6-?fileId=7217886&amp;__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1275768970127" alt="" />

<strong> Can you see the old lady with the large nose, sad smile, and looking down in both illustrations?</strong>
<h2></h2>
<h2>Illustrations of a Perception.</h2>
Look closely at the following illustrations, focusing first on the one on the far left—and then on the one in the middle—and then shift your focus to the one on the far right—and then back to the one in the middle:

<img src="http://www.ocdqblog.com/resource/WindowsLiveWriter-ThePointofViewParadox_9AE6-?fileId=7217887&amp;__SQUARESPACE_CACHEVERSION=1275768990488" alt="" />

&nbsp;

Can you now see both the young lady and the old woman in the middle illustration?

<em><strong>“You’re going to find that many of the truths we cling to depend greatly on our own point of view.” </strong></em>]]></content:encoded>
		<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[]]></excerpt:encoded>
		<wp:post_id>251</wp:post_id>
		<wp:post_date>2012-09-04 10:01:53</wp:post_date>
		<wp:post_date_gmt>2012-09-04 14:01:53</wp:post_date_gmt>
		<wp:comment_status>open</wp:comment_status>

	</item>
	<item>
		<title>There&#039;s more than we can see.</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/theres-more-than-we-can-see/</link>
		<pubDate>Wed, 12 Sep 2012 20:24:35 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=263</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[&nbsp;

<img id="il_fi" src="http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-S8j29EIgf-c/T8cx96QuU6I/AAAAAAAAB9s/JOXIDQXYW2k/s1600/iceberg3.jpg" alt="" width="654" height="437" />

We all want the magic question to ask at the right time to the right person that will lead to a “WOW” moment.  The reality is there is no one question out there that does that but there is a concept that will help you get closer to those “WOW” moments.  If you can grab the concept that it’s not your job to change people as a group leader, your job is to lead them to truth and understanding and allow them to make choices based on their own knowledge.

If you would focus more on trying to understand why they feel the way they do or why they are acting a certain way, it will truly change the way you see them.  So when you have the chance, ask questions that can help you understand where they are emotionally, mentally and maybe even spiritually.

Look below the surface of what you are seeing and hearing.  You will be able to see the big picture of who they really are.  This takes work – remember if you truly want to understand where they are coming from there is always more than you can see.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>

	<item>
		<title>In the begining...</title>
		<link>http://thediscussionproject.com/in-the-begining/</link>
		<pubDate>Mon, 17 Sep 2012 10:58:18 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>Greg</dc:creator>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://thediscussionproject.com/?p=268</guid>
		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="" />

&nbsp;

I don't know if you are a person of Faith or if you have never graced the doors of a church, either way we have all heard the story of Adam and Eve.  I want us to take a few minutes to look at a portion of this story again.  I don't want us to focus so much on the act of what happened but more on How God responded to what they did.

Before we get into that, I want us to have some basis for our thoughts on God and who He is.

Here is one truth (not the only one) that makes this story interesting…
<div>

<strong>God is all knowing. (He knows everything we do weather we tell Him or not)</strong>

</div>
Let me set the story up for you if you have not been to church in awhile.  God gives Adam and Eve free reign in the garden to eat from any tree accept the tree in the center of the garden.  I think God put the tree in the middle of the garden for a reason.  Anyway, the woman Eve, was deceived by a talking snake to eat from the tree in which God told them not to eat.  Once she ate from the tree she gave some to her husband Adam.

This is how the rest of the story plays out:

Genesis 3:8-13 ESV

<strong>8</strong>And they heard the sound of the Lord God walking in the garden in the cool of the day, and the man and his wife hid themselves from the presence of the Lord God among the trees of the garden. <strong>9</strong> But the Lord God called to the man and said to him, <strong>"Where are you?" 10</strong> And he said, "I heard the sound of you in the garden, and I was afraid, because I was naked, and I hid myself." <strong>11</strong> He said, <strong>"Who told you that you were naked? Have you eaten of the tree of which I commanded you not to eat?" 12</strong> The man said, "The woman whom you gave to be with me, she gave me fruit of the tree, and I ate." <strong>13</strong> Then the Lord God said to the woman, <strong>"What is this that you have done?"</strong> The woman said, "The serpent deceived me, and I ate."

I have read this story hundred times but this jumped out at me one time when I was preparing a message for a Sunday morning service.  If God is all knowing, why did he ask Adam and Eve four questions?  Think about it before you answer off the top of your head.

I believe God knows how we work and we wants us to discovery truths instead of told.  We have to own our on "junk".  The only time God made a statement about what they did it was to the snake and to Adam and Eve about what their consequence would be for their decision.  This story challenges me every time I'm about to make a statement to someone about what they should be doing.  My challenge to you is ask questions don't make statements.

&nbsp;]]></content:encoded>
